</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">there could be</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> an increase </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">in </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">the number of </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">families in B</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">ed </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">&amp;</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">B</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">reakfast </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">accommodation</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 17.67pt; padding-left:0.33pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">For both RSLs and LAs with housing stock, the question arises of whether they </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">should </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">take action to evict</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> when rent arrears accrue. Some</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">are revising policy where the Social Sector Size Criteria </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">(SSSC) is </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">biting</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">Questions </span><span style