yle="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">t</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> is</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">of course </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">more cost effective to pay a DHP to someone subject to the national welfare reforms </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">rather </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">than </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">treat them</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> as homeless. However, this obviously undermines the </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">objective of the reforms and places considerable recurring liabilities on future allocations of discretionary funding.</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">LAs</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> have developed innovative methods to ensure that this limited resourc</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">e can be </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">used to maximum effect,</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">such as tapering sums off for those previously supplied with full support; or introducing an element of claimant commitment into the awards </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">- </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">but all this is over and above the normal administration and it places a burden on LAs.</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">  </span></li><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">S</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">ome LAs</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> now make DHP awards in collaboration with Housing Department</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">s</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">, in order</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> to identify alternatives to making a DHP that will be of more benefit to both the tenant and landlord, particularly in the private sector. This has involved supporting the tenant to re-negotiate rents or agreeing to make a DHP until the end of a tenancy a</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">t which time the family will be supported in secu</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">ring alternative accommodation.</span></li><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">Some LAs</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">supplemented their DHP budget</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">, where able,</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> so that more residents can secure settled accommodation</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">; </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">e.g. </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">in overcoming difficulties with the broad scope of the l</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">ocal Broad Rental Market Areas </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">(BRMA) </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">which determine the Local Housing </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">Allowance</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> (LHA)</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> rates</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">The setting of </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">LHA</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> rates at 30th percentile has reduced the availability of accommodation for </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">HB</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> recipients and the nature of the BRMA means that in certain hig</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">h-rent areas, this availability is reduced even further. </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">Some LAs</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">have supplemented their DHP budget</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> on the basis that it is cost effective to do so. </span></li><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">It </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">can be </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">d</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">ifficult </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">to </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">decid</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">e</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> whether </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">to award </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">a DHP</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">  </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">It</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> is supposed to be a short term measure but </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">LAs</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> know </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">that </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">the</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> SSSC</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> and</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">benefit cap </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">have significant </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">long</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">term</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> financial impact</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">In many</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> areas there is a shortage of smaller properties so people cannot be moved into accommodation more suitable for their needs.  </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">I</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">n any case </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">uncertainty </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">regarding future </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">DWP </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">funding for this measure</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> is makes financial planning </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">for this provision </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">difficult for LAs</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">. </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> These problems have been magnified by the migration of claimants from LA areas where the cap has had significant impact.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Direct Payment to Landlords</span></p><ol start="20" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">Claimants w</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">ill not be able to choose to have housing costs paid direct to landlord.  This </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">may</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> be detrimental for LAs as they rely on landlords to provide accommodation for rent in their area</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> There is also</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> an impact for Homelessness sections within LA’s </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">- </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">often dire</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">ct payments </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">are</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> used as leverage to get landlords to supply accommodation for the homeless.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Bold; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">The implications of the changes for claimants, particularly those in vulnerable groups (such as people with disabilities and families with children), and those in </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Bold; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">supported and temporary accommodation.</span></p><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Supported Accommodation</span></p><ol start="21" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">Supported accommodation </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">is a key </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">problem</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">.</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">DWP</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">is</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> aware that there is widespread abuse but they are looking for a "quick fix" which </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">may</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> end up making things worse. They </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">have </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">acknowledged that, t</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">o some extent, excluding exempt accommodation costs from the benefit cap and potentially UC</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> has caused the issue</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">. LAs are spending huge amounts of time investigating schemes and are losing appeals</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">.  </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">One provincial city has</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> in excess of 300 appeals outstand</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">ing where they have restricted exorbitant rents associated with these types of schemes and employ a team leader and 4 policy officers on this issue almost full time. Districts can't afford to do this and face an issue where social services are almost compl</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">icit in the abuse.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Overlapping liability</span></p><ol start="22" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">There is no allowance for 'overlapping' liability when someone moves home.  As a result of this a tenant could lose the property as very often they are </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">required</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> to take the tenancy immediately or </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">risk </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">los</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">ing</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> it</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> whilst still having to give the landlord four </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">weeks notice to quit a property.  This could also affect those that have taken on work and want to move to area of where the job is.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">Four week run</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">-</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; text-decoration:underline">on</span></p><ol start="23" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">There is no 4 week run</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">-</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">on when someone starts work.  This </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">may</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> deter people moving into work as they will still have to pay their rent whilst waiting for their first salary payment</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> which is very often in arrears.  </span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:12pt 0pt 6pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Bold; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">Treatment of housing costs within Universal Credit.</span></p><ol start="24" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">Lessons need</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> to be learned from historic precedent.  When the modern HB scheme was introduced in 1982 one of the main drivers was the failure of the then DHSS to properly manage Housing Allowance that was awarded as part of Supplementary Benefit.  </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">DHSS</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> did not verify the housing status of claimants and merely awarded a cash sum in addition to Supplementary Benefit entitlement</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> without any sufficient verification of the tenancy</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">.  This problem was graphically revealed with the prosecutions arising from ‘Op</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">eration Major’ in Oxford, in which over </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">170</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> people were found to be ‘staying’ in the same 4-bedded house on the same night.  The Institute is not convinced that the arrangements for the housing element </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">within</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> UC will be sufficient to ensure that type of fr</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">aud does not reappear.</span></li><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">he </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">treatment of</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> housing costs in the reformed welfare system is </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">presently </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">un</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">clear and this presents a serious risk for claimants, landlords and tax payers.</span></li><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">The recent</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> publication of the National Audit Office (NAO) report </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘Universal </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">credit: early progress’ </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">is highly critical of the lack of detailed view or blueprint of how </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">UC</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> is meant to work, the IT systems and security of procedures to support UC.  </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">The Institute fully supports those findings.  </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">So far, UC has been tested in few pathf</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">inder sites.  HB has been excluded from the pathfinder scope and has not therefore been tested at all. Compatibility with UC for 5</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">m</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">illion</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> HB customers, some of whom are extremely vulnerable, has yet to be established.  </span></li><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">O</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">f the project areas listed as part</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> of early progress in designing UC (sanctions, payments, job search, disregards, real time information for earnings and child care costs </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">etc.</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">) rent is not mentioned throughout the report. </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> T</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">here has been no realistic assessment of the resources required to</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> deliver </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">the </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">housing </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">element </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">within UC.  Without this assessment, DWP </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">can have</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> no understanding of the decisions surrounding liability for, and calculation of rent.  And without this, the system will be extremely vulnerable to systematic fraud attack and c</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">ustomer error. </span></li><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">he proposed UC system will allow many losses because of official error.  The DWP does not have the expertise in assessing or paying rent costs and has had limited </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">contact with </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">LAs</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> to transfer the skills and knowledge needed to deliver an effective and </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">robust</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> service.  </span></li><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">The value of </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">HB</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> overpayments has show</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">n</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> a rising trend since 2010/11. Preliminary estimates for 2012/13 are 5.3% of expenditure, or £1270m.  This is almost equal to t</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">he peak of 5.5% in 2005/06 and despite the current range of assurance, security and data sharing across </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">LAs</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">.  As yet, none of these assurances have been transferred to UC.  </span></li><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">The Centre for London report </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">‘Stressed: A review of London’s Private Rental Sector</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">’, </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">although limited to London, is probably the only independent report on the private rental sector.  The report highlights the impact of welfare system changes on rent costs and property availability.  From initial surveys, the report highlights among oth</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">er items: </span></li></ol><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">40% of London landlords reported they planned to cease letting to HB /LHA tenants specifically because of LHA reforms;</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">38% of London landlords reported they had taken action to evict tenants because of LHA reforms, compared with 25% in the rest </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">of Great Britain; and</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 28.06pt; padding-left:7.94pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">30% of London landlords reported they were no longer renewing some HB/ LHA tenancies compared with 14% in the rest of Great Britain.</span></li></ul><ol start="31" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">The report also highlighted that because of measures in the Localism Act, </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">LAs</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> are</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> making increased use of the private rental sector to discharge duties under homelessness legislation. </span></li><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">With little confidence in the current system and lack of clarity around housing costs within UC, private and social landlords are unlikely to support fu</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">rther reforms.  There is a strong case, therefore, for excluding housing costs from UC for the foreseeable future. </span></li><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">It is most</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> worrying that HB hasn't yet been part of the UC pathfinders</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">,</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> therefore it remains untested</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">;</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> but it's also too vague, particularly</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> when it comes to how much will be paid across to landlords where tenants fall into arrears. </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">T</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">his isn’t an issue facing authorities with HB currently, since the maximum amount is clearly set, but with UC the lines are blurred, since the final payment will </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">not clearly identify sums attributable to the housing cost element. </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">Limitations are placed on the sum of deductions which can be made, within </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">legislation,</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> but this simply states </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">a </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">maximum of the standard allowance could be exceeded in relation to housing </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">costs where the Secretary of State believes it to be in the claimant’s best interests</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">As a result of UC being paid monthly in arrears and paid direct to the claimant it is inevitable that a </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">significant</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> number of families will be in rent arrears and could be for </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">the first time.   Many LAs have expressed concern that a large proportion of households will be unable to manage their money effectively, leading to rent arrears, possible eviction and furthe</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">r in</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">debtedness – and ultimately push additional costs onto LAs.</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">There is concern that within UC it will be difficult to check the breakdown within the total to ensure mistakes have not been made. </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> E</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">mployers need to be aware that the checking and verification </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">procedures when a new claim is made could identify payroll queries if the claimant disputes the earnings t</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">hat have informed the UC award.</span></li><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">Housing plans are reliant on maintaining rental income levels and there is a strong possibility these plans will not b</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">e fully delivered.  This is an issue for </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">both LAs with</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> retained stock </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">and H</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">ousing </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">A</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">ssociations</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> as well.  </span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:0pt 0pt 10pt 18pt; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">IRRV urges the Government to reflect on the emerging findings regarding inclusion of support for housing costs, and delay inclusion of this element w</span><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt">ithin UC until other elements of the new system have bedded in.</span></li></ol><p style="font-size:11pt; line-height:115%; margin:6pt 0pt 6pt 18pt"><span style="font-family:DIN-Regular; font-size:11pt; font-style:italic">27 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>